&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mars:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mars has two moons, named Phobos and Deimos.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are small and irregularly shaped, and are thought to be captured asteroids.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Jupiter&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;J&lt;strong&gt;upiter has the largest number of moons in the solar system, with 72&amp;nbsp;moons co&lt;/strong&gt;nfirmed as of September 2021.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;text-align: justify;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;After the discovery of&amp;nbsp;13&amp;nbsp;new moons of Jupiter, it accounts for a total of 95&amp;nbsp;natural satellites, which is the largest among all the planets.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Some of its most famous moons include Io, Europa, Ganymede, and Callisto.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Uranus: &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Uranus has 28&amp;nbsp;known moons&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Some of its largest moons are Miranda, Ariel, Umbriel, Titania, and Oberon.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Neptune&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Neptune has 16&amp;nbsp;known moons as of September 2021.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Its largest moon, Triton, is notable for being the only large moon in the solar system to orbit in the opposite direction of its planet&amp;#39;s rotation.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Overall, the number of moons for each planet is subject to change as more moons are discovered or confirmed.&lt;br /&gt;
